<br>
     &quot;Surprisingly, coal burning power plants release several hundred time more radioactivity per day than do nuclear power plants.  This radioactivity comes from the uranium, radium, thorium, and polonium which were trapped in the coal during its formation.  Each year, about 20,000 tons of uranium is mixed in with the one billion tons of coal now mined.&quot; (pp. 38 ) <br>
<br>
I also found his little sub-chapter on using electric cars that are charged via coal burning plants interesting:<br>
<br>
&quot;If this [electricity generated for electric cars] is generated by coal-burning power plants, the death toll from air pollution could easily increase rather than decrease as many people expect.  This is based on the fact that most air pollution studies indicate a relationship between sulfur dioxide and increase death rates.  Automobiles presently release only about 1.6 percent of the sulfur dioxide emitted each year.  Coal burning, on the other hand, releases 88 percent of the sulfur dioxide generated.&quot; (pp. 39 )   <br>
<br>
In case anyone is wondering why cars release so little sulfur dioxide as compared to coal burning plants, it because the manufacturing process for gasoline elminates a lot of the sulfur dioxide.  The part about electric cars is just logical.  The energy the cars themselves use might be cleaner but if they get that energy from a &quot;dirty&quot; source, pollutants are still being thrown into the air, and much deadlier ones.  Ah, what I'd do for a breath of clean air.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->      <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A> at: 10/23/02 2:43:04 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 53<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/23/02 3:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=87.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Coal combustion</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.ornl.gov/ORNLReview/rev26-34/text/colmain.html">This article from Oak Ridge National Laboratory</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> was a favorite on the old Yahoo board. It gives the specifics on radioactive coal ash, and even proposes mining ash heaps as a source of radioactive materials. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclearharbinger>Nuclear Harbinger</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ditl.org/Gengrafix/smallcomspin.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet